I love him.

248
00:23:14,493 --> 00:23:16,484
Then I like him.

249
00:23:29,574 --> 00:23:31,542
Hey, Bob.
Hey.

250
00:23:31,610 --> 00:23:34,443
- Oh, Mrs. Bergstrom. Hello.
How are you?
- Sylvia.

251
00:23:34,513 --> 00:23:36,504
It's so lovely to see you.

252
00:23:36,581 --> 00:23:39,709
And you. You're looking beautiful.
Thank you.
This is my husband, Ted.

253
00:23:39,785 --> 00:23:41,946
Hello.
Pleased to meet you.

254
00:23:42,020 --> 00:23:44,147
We've heard a lot about you.
Likewise.

255
00:23:44,222 --> 00:23:47,680
How are you enjoying yourselves?
Hello. Oh, we're having
such a nice time.

256
00:23:47,759 --> 00:23:49,954
Good.
Thank you.

257
00:23:50,028 --> 00:23:52,053
You've made us feel so at home.
Hasn't she?

258
00:23:52,130 --> 00:23:54,997
If I close my eyes,
I could be back in Mytholmroyd.

259
00:23:55,066 --> 00:23:57,057
Your hem's up in the front, darling.

260
00:23:57,135 --> 00:23:59,194
Oh.
Elizabeth, meet Ted.

261
00:23:59,271 --> 00:24:01,831
Ted, Elizabeth Brooks.
How do you do?

262
00:24:01,907 --> 00:24:05,570
My, aren't you
the catch of the day.
Ted is going to be a great poet.

263
00:24:05,644 --> 00:24:08,078
His last book won--
What was that?

264
00:24:08,146 --> 00:24:10,205
The New York Center Poetry Prize.

265
00:24:10,282 --> 00:24:13,308
It's rather good.
It's the, uh,
Hawk in the Rain.

266
00:24:13,385 --> 00:24:15,319
Really wonderful.
You read it?

267
00:24:15,387 --> 00:24:17,582
Yes. Of course.

268
00:24:17,656 --> 00:24:20,022
What did you think
of the poem about the giraffe?

269
00:24:20,091 --> 00:24:22,491
Oh, listen
to that accent.

270
00:24:22,561 --> 00:24:26,258
There wasn't a poem
about a giraffe.
Say something else.

271
00:24:28,800 --> 00:24:30,893
I need a drink.
Uh, excuse me, ladies.

272
00:24:57,295 --> 00:24:59,456
This Sylvia's father?

273
00:24:59,531 --> 00:25:02,898
Mm-hmm. Yes.
Bumblebees were his specialty.

274
00:25:02,968 --> 00:25:05,562
It's all he ever thought about.

275
00:25:05,637 --> 00:25:07,696
Before the war,
back in Germany,

276
00:25:07,772 --> 00:25:11,264
his colleagues always called him
der Bienenkönig.

277
00:25:11,343 --> 00:25:14,278
That means--
King of the Bees.

278
00:25:14,346 --> 00:25:16,371
Yes, that's right.

279
00:25:16,448 --> 00:25:18,541
That was Otto.
King of the Bees.

280
00:25:21,386 --> 00:25:24,321
You must forgive my friends, Ted.

281
00:25:24,389 --> 00:25:26,550
They, uh, haven't had
the advantages you have.

282
00:25:28,426 --> 00:25:30,417
And what might they be?

283
00:25:30,495 --> 00:25:33,430
Having to fight for what you want.

284
00:25:34,866 --> 00:25:37,801
That's why she's in love
with you, you know.
Sylvia, I mean.

285
00:25:38,870 --> 00:25:42,397
Oh, my God. There were--
Oh, there were--

286
00:25:42,474 --> 00:25:45,136
I don't--
I don't mean to sound disloyal,
but there were...

287
00:25:45,210 --> 00:25:47,144
a lot of other boys,

288
00:25:47,212 --> 00:25:49,442
but they didn't scare her.

289
00:25:50,515 --> 00:25:52,574
She rather frightened them, I think.

290
00:25:55,220 --> 00:25:57,950
You're--

291
00:25:58,023 --> 00:26:00,548
You're very different.

292
00:26:00,625 --> 00:26:04,823
But I think you frightened her,
and that's why she likes you.

293
00:26:04,896 --> 00:26:08,024
You think I'd hurt her.
No, I wouldn't hurt her.

294
00:26:12,003 --> 00:26:16,303
Do you know that we found her
right where you're standing?
Right under there, near the boards.

295
00:26:17,576 --> 00:26:20,739
We thought she was dead,
she was so pale, so white.

296
00:26:22,581 --> 00:26:24,708
Some people want to be found.
Sylvia didn't.

297
00:26:24,783 --> 00:26:26,910
She just...

298
00:26:26,985 --> 00:26:29,886
crawled into a hole
and waited to die.

299
00:26:31,523 --> 00:26:33,753
Be good to her.

300
00:26:33,825 --> 00:26:35,952
Always.

301
00:28:03,381 --> 00:28:05,406
Hi.
Hope you like fish.

302
00:28:05,483 --> 00:28:08,281
Wow, look at those.
My God.

303
00:28:08,353 --> 00:28:10,753
Did you have fun?
Uh-huh.

304
00:28:10,822 --> 00:28:14,588
It finally cooled down.
It was so hot earlier, wasn't it?
You tell me.

305
00:28:14,659 --> 00:28:17,719
I look a bit... messy because
I started baking, and I made--

306
00:28:17,796 --> 00:28:20,788
Baking?
I made one real cream cake,
but it went a bit funny in the center.

307
00:28:20,865 --> 00:28:23,425
I just decided to throw it out
and start over.

308
00:28:23,501 --> 00:28:26,800
But the funny thing is,
the second one looks nicer than
the first one anyway.

309
00:28:26,871 --> 00:28:29,135
I thought you were gonna write.

310
00:28:31,209 --> 00:28:34,076
Do you know, some husbands
would be happy that their wives...

311
00:28:34,145 --> 00:28:36,409
stayed home
and baked them some nice cakes.

312
00:28:39,184 --> 00:28:43,018
I am happy.
I'd just be happier
if you were writing.

313
00:28:43,088 --> 00:28:45,147
I've got the whole summer to write.

314
00:29:32,771 --> 00:29:35,239
How was your walk?
Good.

315
00:29:41,279 --> 00:29:44,146
Got a poem. A good one.

316
00:29:46,718 --> 00:29:48,845
You?

317
00:29:48,920 --> 00:29:50,911
I'm dried up.

318
00:29:50,989 --> 00:29:52,980
That's 'cause you've got nothing to say.

319
00:29:53,057 --> 00:29:55,150
I'm not a real writer.
Never will be.

320
00:29:55,226 --> 00:29:58,093
I'm no good.
You make great cakes.

321
00:30:06,171 --> 00:30:08,537
You know what your trouble is?

322
00:30:10,008 --> 00:30:13,671
I have a husband who thinks
he can tell me how to write poetry?

323
00:30:13,745 --> 00:30:15,736
There's no secret to it.

324
00:30:15,814 --> 00:30:18,374
You've just gotta
pick a subject and...

325
00:30:18,449 --> 00:30:20,417
stick your head into it.

326
00:30:22,120 --> 00:30:24,418
You've got to write.
That's what poets do.

327
00:30:24,489 --> 00:30:27,356
Yes, well, that's easy for you to say.

328
00:30:28,626 --> 00:30:32,585
You go out for a bike ride
and come back with
an epic in hexameters.

329
00:30:34,165 --> 00:30:36,725
I sit down to write,
I get a bake sale.

330
00:30:41,840 --> 00:30:43,774
Do you know what--

331
00:30:43,842 --> 00:30:45,833
Do you know what my trouble is?

332
00:30:47,045 --> 00:30:49,741
Is that I don't have a subject.

333
00:30:51,449 --> 00:30:54,418
The novel, Falcon Yard,
what's that about?

334
00:30:57,255 --> 00:31:00,520
It's... about a girl who meets a boy.

335
00:31:00,592 --> 00:31:03,993
No. What's it really about?
You and me.

336
00:31:04,062 --> 00:31:05,927
What's it really about?

337
00:31:05,997 --> 00:31:08,158
Me.

338
00:31:08,233 --> 00:31:11,031
A girl who spends her summer
at the beach?

339
00:31:11,102 --> 00:31:13,332
No, see--
No, that's not really me.

340
00:31:13,404 --> 00:31:16,498
Yes, it is.
You told me it was about you.

341
00:31:17,575 --> 00:31:22,012
What I'm trying to say is
that you've already got your subject.
It's you.

342
00:31:22,080 --> 00:31:24,571
And you keep skirting
round the issue.

343
00:31:24,649 --> 00:31:28,141
- You keep flowering it up. You keep--
- All right, all right, all right.

344
00:31:29,821 --> 00:31:31,812
Shit.

345
00:31:32,891 --> 00:31:35,291
- jesus Christ.
- What?

346
00:31:37,328 --> 00:31:39,296
The tide's dragging us out.

347
00:31:39,364 --> 00:31:41,332
I'm not gonna get us back in.

348
00:31:45,637 --> 00:31:47,628
People drown like this.

349
00:31:58,583 --> 00:32:00,608
I tried to drown myself once.

350
00:32:04,689 --> 00:32:07,214
I swam out in the sea
as far as I could,

351
00:32:07,292 --> 00:32:09,692
but it just spat me out like a cork.

352
00:32:11,596 --> 00:32:14,292
I guess it didn't want me.

353
00:32:17,902 --> 00:32:19,893
You know, it's funny,

354
00:32:23,808 --> 00:32:26,902
I was always happy
until I was nine years old.

355
00:32:28,780 --> 00:32:31,044
I was always in one piece.

356
00:32:34,452 --> 00:32:36,443
Then my father died.

357
00:32:43,928 --> 00:32:47,830
Full fathom five my father lies:

358
00:32:47,899 --> 00:32:51,995
Of his bones were coral made:
Those were pearls that were his eyes.''

359
00:33:14,258 --> 00:33:17,352
Destroy.! Destroy.! Destroy.!

360
00:33:17,428 --> 00:33:20,295
hums the underconsciousness.

361
00:33:20,365 --> 00:33:23,698
Love and produce!
Love and produce!

362
00:33:23,768 --> 00:33:25,759
cackles the upper consciousness.

363
00:33:25,837 --> 00:33:29,204
And the world hears only
the love and produce cackle.

364
00:33:29,273 --> 00:33:33,437
Refuses to hear the hum
of destruction underneath...

365
00:33:33,511 --> 00:33:35,911
until such time as it
will have to hear.

366
00:33:35,980 --> 00:33:39,882
The American has got to destroy!

367
00:33:41,219 --> 00:33:43,619
It is his destiny.

368
00:33:43,688 --> 00:33:46,088
And finally, this...

369
00:33:47,492 --> 00:33:49,551
poem by Yeats, I think...

370
00:33:51,863 --> 00:33:54,525
illustrates...

371
00:33:54,599 --> 00:33:56,590
that point rather well.

372
00:33:59,537 --> 00:34:02,165
Well, at least I hope it does.

373
00:34:03,408 --> 00:34:05,399
Excuse me.

374
00:34:07,512 --> 00:34:10,174
The Sorrow of Love.

375
00:34:11,849 --> 00:34:15,012
The quarrel of the sparrows in the eaves,

376
00:34:15,086 --> 00:34:19,022
the full round moon
and the star-laden sky,

377
00:34:19,090 --> 00:34:22,526
and the loud song
of the ever-singing leaves,

378
00:34:22,593 --> 00:34:25,653
had hid away earth's old and weary cry.

379
00:34:25,730 --> 00:34:28,290
And then you came...

380
00:34:28,366 --> 00:34:31,699
with those red mournful lips,

381
00:34:31,769 --> 00:34:34,533
and with you came
the whole of the world's tears,

382
00:34:34,605 --> 00:34:37,870
and all the sorrows ofher laboring ships,

383
00:34:37,942 --> 00:34:41,105
and all the burden ofher myriad years.

384
00:34:41,179 --> 00:34:44,580
And now the sparrows warring in the eaves,

385
00:34:44,649 --> 00:34:48,483
the crumbling moon,
the white stars in the sky,

386
00:34:48,553 --> 00:34:51,818
and the loud chanting of the unquiet leaves,

387
00:34:51,889 --> 00:34:55,791
are shaken with earth's old and weary cry.

388
00:34:57,128 --> 00:34:59,119
Thank you.

389
00:35:07,805 --> 00:35:09,796
Thank you.

390
00:35:14,445 --> 00:35:17,312
Thank you very much.
That's very kind. Take care.
I was so impressed.

391
00:35:17,381 --> 00:35:19,212
Bye.
Yeah. Bye-bye. Thank you.

392
00:35:19,283 --> 00:35:21,979
Mr. Hughes, uh, your voice--

393
00:35:22,053 --> 00:35:24,180
so powerful.

394
00:35:24,255 --> 00:35:27,315
But, uh, what did you think
of the words?

395
00:35:27,391 --> 00:35:29,586
The words?

396
00:35:29,660 --> 00:35:32,493
So when is your next book
coming out?

397
00:35:32,563 --> 00:35:34,827
Well, when I've written it.

398
00:35:36,834 --> 00:35:40,099
Oh, it must be wonderful
to be married to such a great poet.

399
00:35:40,171 --> 00:35:42,731
Yes, it is. It is.

400
00:35:42,807 --> 00:35:44,832
Would you excuse us
for just a moment?

401
00:35:44,909 --> 00:35:47,036
Sure.
Excuse me.

402
00:35:49,413 --> 00:35:52,211
I'm sorry. I just--
I'm so exhausted,

403
00:35:52,283 --> 00:35:54,683
and I've got a stack of papers
this high to get through.

404
00:35:54,752 --> 00:35:56,879
Do you mind
if we go now or in a minute?

405
00:35:56,954 --> 00:36:00,117
I'm gonna have to say thanks
to Merwin for that review.

406
00:36:00,191 --> 00:36:02,659
And Len Baskin's here, so I--
Who's Len Baskin?

407
00:36:02,727 --> 00:36:06,128
Len Baskin. He organized all this.
Oh, right. Right.

408
00:36:06,197 --> 00:36:09,564
So, look, take the car.

409
00:36:09,634 --> 00:36:12,102
All right.

410
00:36:12,170 --> 00:36:14,161
I'll see you later.

411
00:36:22,547 --> 00:36:24,538
Right.

412
00:37:12,496 --> 00:37:14,487
Is Mr. Hughes in?

413
00:37:14,565 --> 00:37:16,999
No.

414
00:37:19,570 --> 00:37:22,038
He said he'd look at my poetry.

415
00:37:24,775 --> 00:37:27,642
He said it would be okay.

416
00:37:32,917 --> 00:37:35,750
I'm sorry if I disturbed you.

417
00:39:30,000 --> 00:39:31,991
Yeah.

418
00:39:39,744 --> 00:39:42,269
Who is she?

419
00:39:43,714 --> 00:39:46,444
She's nobody.

420
00:39:46,517 --> 00:39:49,213
A student. She was...

421
00:39:50,521 --> 00:39:54,753
in that creative writing class I--
I talked to.

422
00:39:54,825 --> 00:39:57,453
She'd written all these poems.
I took pity on her.

423
00:40:03,868 --> 00:40:06,928
- You think I'm fucking her.
- Are you?

424
00:40:07,004 --> 00:40:09,495
Oh, for Christ's sake!

425
00:40:09,573 --> 00:40:11,837
This place is really
getting to you, isn't it?

426
00:40:11,909 --> 00:40:14,810
This bunch of dried up,
malicious old women...

427
00:40:14,879 --> 00:40:18,406
who think their men
are gonna get a taste for fresh meat.

428
00:40:19,483 --> 00:40:22,543
As a matter of fact,
I'm not fucking her.

429
00:40:22,620 --> 00:40:26,283
But if I do start fucking the students,
you'll be the first to know.

430
00:41:37,661 --> 00:41:40,596
Last night--
I--

431
00:41:40,664 --> 00:41:43,189
I was very tired. I--

432
00:41:44,935 --> 00:41:48,462
I've organized everything so I won't--
I won't be quite so tired, um--

433
00:41:48,539 --> 00:41:50,473
I'm sorry.

434
00:41:51,709 --> 00:41:54,041
It's not just you.
It's me as well.

435
00:41:55,779 --> 00:41:57,770
I can't write here.

436
00:42:03,621 --> 00:42:05,612
We should go back to England.

437
00:42:05,689 --> 00:42:07,680
And live on what?

438
00:42:11,228 --> 00:42:13,219
We'll survive, lovely.

439
00:42:58,509 --> 00:43:01,672
Do you see that?

440
00:43:04,982 --> 00:43:07,815
That's the world.

441
00:43:16,794 --> 00:43:18,762
Page 1 4,

442
00:43:18,829 --> 00:43:21,024
on line--line 1 4.

443
00:43:21,098 --> 00:43:23,965
Yes. Page 1 4, line 1 4.

444
00:43:24,034 --> 00:43:26,002
There is an E-- Yes.

445
00:43:27,104 --> 00:43:30,904
No, two. Two P's.
Will you get that?

446
00:43:32,042 --> 00:43:34,602
Uh, page 40.

447
00:43:35,646 --> 00:43:37,637
Yes. Next--
Line eight.

448
00:43:37,715 --> 00:43:41,583
Next the new moon's curve.''

449
00:43:41,652 --> 00:43:43,711
Oh, those guys are all the same.

450
00:43:43,787 --> 00:43:45,880
I mean, I wouldn't have thought--
Right.

451
00:43:47,391 --> 00:43:49,655
Right.
I mean, after Hawk in the Rain,
they, uh--

452
00:43:49,727 --> 00:43:53,060
No.
the literary establishment were all hoping
your next book would be an...

453
00:43:53,130 --> 00:43:55,098
anticlimax.

454
00:43:55,165 --> 00:43:58,032
But I'm pleased to say you've
confounded them and outdone yourself.

455
00:43:58,102 --> 00:44:00,400
- It's really quite wonderful.
- On the back page.

456
00:44:01,705 --> 00:44:04,401
In the back jacket.

457
00:44:04,475 --> 00:44:06,841
Uh, I've just made some coffee.
Would you like a cup?

458
00:44:06,910 --> 00:44:10,209
Well, I think you can speak
to the agent about that.
All right?

459
00:44:12,016 --> 00:44:13,950
- Hello.
- Hello.

460
00:44:14,018 --> 00:44:17,078
You must be Mr. Alvarez.
Yes, indeed.
And you must be Mrs. Hughes?

461
00:44:17,154 --> 00:44:19,782
Night Shift?

462
00:44:19,857 --> 00:44:21,950
Uh

463
00:44:22,026 --> 00:44:24,790
Night Shift. It's a poem
you printed in the Observer.

464
00:44:24,862 --> 00:44:27,626
Oh, yes.
Night Shift. Yes.
It was a good poem.

465
00:44:27,698 --> 00:44:30,861
Well, yes, I know. I wrote it.

466
00:44:30,934 --> 00:44:33,459
Oh, you're Sylvia Plath.
I am.

467
00:44:33,537 --> 00:44:36,370
Oh. Nice to meet you.
And you.

468
00:44:36,440 --> 00:44:39,204
Uh, tell me, have you written
any others or--
Yes, I have.

469
00:44:39,276 --> 00:44:41,267
Actually, I have a, uh,

470
00:44:41,345 --> 00:44:44,405
book of poems coming out
very shortly called The Colossus.

471
00:44:44,481 --> 00:44:47,712
I'd love to read them.
Thank you. It would be an honor.

472
00:44:49,853 --> 00:44:53,482
I spoke to George about it last week
and, uh, he was quite optimistic.

473
00:44:53,557 --> 00:44:55,491
It might take another six months.

474
00:44:55,559 --> 00:44:58,153
The whole thing,
it's about putting a face to a name.

475
00:44:58,228 --> 00:45:01,061
For them to put, you know,
your name to duh, duh, duh,
and likewise.

476
00:45:01,131 --> 00:45:03,691
I mean, we've got Charlie Hetheringham
here from the T.L.S.

477
00:45:03,767 --> 00:45:06,429
There's Robinson
from the Critical Quarterly.
That one there?

478
00:45:06,503 --> 00:45:09,336
Yeah. And, um, there's, uh,
the Telegraph there and the Times.

479
00:45:09,406 --> 00:45:12,170
And, uh--
Oh,yes,you see that chap with
the big ears?

480
00:45:12,242 --> 00:45:14,176
He's easy. He's from the Listener.

481
00:45:14,244 --> 00:45:16,269
So, it's a good turnout,you know.

482
00:45:16,346 --> 00:45:19,179
That's a good sign, isn't it,
that they all came?

483
00:45:19,249 --> 00:45:23,310
Well, yes, of course.
I mean, don't get your hopes up too high,
but, yes it is. It really is.

484
00:45:23,387 --> 00:45:26,948
They're all bloody
civil servants moonlighting
as journalists.

485
00:45:27,024 --> 00:45:29,857
It's their job to protect
the status quo.

486
00:45:32,429 --> 00:45:35,660
That's the toughest.
Mr. Robinson.

487
00:45:35,733 --> 00:45:37,724
Mr. Robinson.

488
00:45:37,801 --> 00:45:39,735
You forgot this.

489
00:45:39,803 --> 00:45:42,169
Oh, uh, thanks.

490
00:45:42,239 --> 00:45:44,104
Do you think
you might be reviewing it?

491
